    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-10-13T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-10-13T07:00:00-05:00" n="134"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 296/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-10-13T12:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 13, 1922—12 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>397. Your 307 of October 9. I have conferred with Morgan and Boyden.<note n="12"
                        xml:id="d134fn12">American unofficial representative on the Reparation
                        Commission.</note> All agree that the situation is critical and that some
                    action is imperative. However, Morgan declines flatly to take any initiative
                    maintaining that it is a political matter and the initiative must come from the
                    governments. He is sensitive about restrictions imposed last time on bankers
                        commission<note n="13" xml:id="d134fn13">A committee of bankers, including
                        J. P. Morgan, appointed by the Reparation Commission in April, 1922, to
                        consider conditions under which Germany might raise foreign loans to redeem
                        in part the reparation debt. The committee reported on June 10. The text of
                        the report was released in Paris to the press on the same date.</note> but
                    is willing to serve again on it if it is reconvened with restrictions
                    removed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
